Lock the story's voice before any prose is written. The voice document is the
operational descendant of the vision: where the vision names a mood, the voice
makes concrete, checkable commitments every one of the {{ passage_count }} passages
must obey.

THE VOICE CHARACTERIZES THE WHOLE STORY, NOT EVERY PARAGRAPH. A reader should feel
this voice across the arc — not braced against it in every sentence. Within any one
passage most prose is plain, clear, and load-bearing; the voice's distinctive
qualities (its imagery, its heightened cadence, its richest diction) surface only at
the few moments that earn them. So coin a voice that reads as unmistakable over the
whole book while leaving ample room for plain sentences to carry the events, and
frame every commitment below so it can be applied with restraint rather than
saturated into every line. Clarity always outranks atmosphere — a reader must be
able to say what happened.

VISION: {{ vision.genre }}{% if vision.subgenre %} / {{ vision.subgenre }}{% endif %}, {{ vision.tone }}.
Themes: {{ vision.themes | join("; ") }}. Audience: {{ vision.audience }}.
POV hint (advisory): {{ vision.pov_hint or "none" }}.
PREMISE (the author's ask): {{ vision.premise }}

THE STORY'S SHAPE:
{% for d in dilemmas %}
- {{ d.question }} ({{ d.role }})
{% endfor %}
Endings: {{ endings | join(" / ") }}.

THE CAST (these spellings are canonical — any name the voice uses must match
one of them exactly):
{% for e in cast %}
- {{ e.name }}{% if e.pronouns %} ({{ e.pronouns }}){% endif %}: {{ e.concept }}
{% endfor %}

{% if research %}
CRAFT NOTES — voices and craft material from the author's corpus. Advisory, and
for the style exemplars among them a hard rule: they are a contrasting spread, a
map of the possibility space, never candidates — commit to a voice none of them
uses. If a decision below drifts toward sounding like one, move it. Never quote
or imitate a note's wording.

{{ research }}
{% endif %}
{% if roster %}
THE DECLARED SCHEME (already resolved — describe it, do not re-decide it).
The narration follows exactly these heads: {% for r in roster %}{{ r.name }}{% if not loop.last %}, {% endif %}{% endfor %}.
{% if carrier %}The scheme's deviant register is carried by {{ carrier.name }}.{% endif %}
{% endif %}
Decide:
- pov: the story's viewpoint SCHEME — whose head(s), how close. A single fixed
  viewpoint reads "second person", or "third person limited (NAME)". A rotating
  scheme (only when the POV hint asks for one) reads "third person limited,
  rotating at passage boundaries among NAME, NAME, ..." — each passage stays
  inside ONE of those heads (the engine assigns which). Every NAME must be a
  viewpoint character's name spelled exactly as the cast lists it. Never coin or
  vary a name here: every passage and its review will be held to this string.
  When a DECLARED SCHEME is shown above, its heads are the scheme — name
  exactly those, no more, no fewer.
- tense: past or present.
- interlude: "" for almost every story. Set it ONLY when the POV hint names a
  marked deviant register woven into the scheme (occasional first-person journal
  entries, letters, diary pages): one line naming its form, person, and tense,
  with the narrator's name IN PARENTHESES exactly as the pov names its
  viewpoint — "first-person past-tense journal entries (NAME)" — spelled
  exactly as the cast lists it. The parenthetical is required: it is how the
  engine checks the narrator against the cast. When a DECLARED SCHEME above
  names a register carrier, the narrator is that character. Passages the
  engine marks as interludes are written and reviewed against this line
  instead of the pov/tense above.
- diction: the register in a phrase ("spare, salt-worn, literary").
- rhythm: one line of sentence-rhythm rules — set a PLAIN baseline (most
  sentences straightforward and complete, varied in length) and reserve
  elaboration or a heightened cadence for emphasis, so the rhythm is a default to
  depart from, not a maximal pattern the writer must hit in every sentence.
- imagery: where the voice's images come from — the sensory domains it draws
  on and their limits ("tide, oil-light, worked rope; dread lives in objects,
  never in similes"). The writer reaches for this palette instead of copying
  phrasing it has seen, so make it generative: domains, not example sentences.
  It is spent at a few charged moments per passage, not in every description — a
  palette to reach for, never a coat of paint for every sentence.
- dialogue: how speech behaves on the page — length, tags, what stays unsaid
  ("brief, unornamented; tags are 'said' or nothing").
- banned: 3-6 patterns to forbid — each a specific construction the reviewer
  can find literally in the prose AND the writer can avoid without hobbling
  ordinary sentences. The review enforces these VERBATIM, so choose them with
  care. Good bans: "exclamation marks", "rhetorical questions to the reader",
  "second-person address", "sentences opening with a participial phrase". NEVER
  ban a common word — forbidding "as" or "like" outlaws ordinary prose ("as the
  river rose" is not a simile), and NEVER ban a vague label the writer cannot
  mechanically check ("direct metaphor", "purple prose", "clichés"): an
  over-broad or unactionable ban traps every passage. NEVER phrase a ban as a
  complement ("anything other than X", "tags other than 'said'") — that is not
  a construction the reviewer can find literally, and it invites misreading
  ordinary grammar (a speaker's name after "said") as a violation; a rule about
  what speech SHOULD look like belongs in `dialogue`, stated positively. Ban
  the construction that would puncture the tone, never a word ordinary
  sentences need.
- notes: one line of guidance for the writer.
